                 --Basic Wizard Rules--

Wizards are expected to act in a manner appropriate to their positions
as coders, caretakers, and administrators of DarkWind. Wizards must be
aware that they are no longer players, and must maintain an appropriate
distance from mortal affairs. Furthermore, as authority figures on the
mud, they must be careful not to abuse their powers in any way.

The following list is not an exhaustive list of wizard rules. There will
always be situations that are not covered by the rules listed here where
a wizard may be required to make a judgement call. Note that wizard
rules have very little to do with personal advancement as in the case
of player rules. Rather, they relate to things like trustworthiness,
competence and good judgement. Thus, when making a judgement call, be
aware that a bad judgement reflects poorly on a wizard, very similarly
in some ways to blatant breaking of rules. If in doubt, refer problems
to a higher ranking wizard.

Additionally, you will agree to and follow the Code of Conduct (see:
wizhelp conduct)

Finally, ignorance is no excuse for breaking a rule, and punishments
are meted out in an individual basis.


1. Wizards may not provide access to their character to any other
   person.

2. Wizards may not erase or otherwise edit other wizards' files.  The
   same applies to system files.  Access to these files is generally
   protected, but it's conceivable that some things may be overlooked.
   If the wizard discovers that s/he has greater access than they
   should, it should be reported to an IMP+.

3. Copying another wizard's work without prior consent.

4. Interfering with players in any way.  This includes healing players;
   providing additional stats, XP, money, levels, alignment, etc through
   patching; and giving players objects or money.  This is not a
   comprehensive list by any means.  In general: if the character isn't
   your test character, don't mess with 'em.  Period.

   4a. The occasional boon or similar global blessing given by an IMP+ is
       not considered interference.

5. Abuse of wizard powers.

6. Disobeying higher-up wizards.

7. Encouraging players to break rules.

8. Giving out information on areas, systems, weapons etc., with the
   exception of information found in player documentation or information
   approved from distribution by an IMP+.
   for distribution by an IMP.

